  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international guidelines established\n- Limited scope and enforcement\n\n2. 1980s-1990s\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- More comprehensive international standards\n- Increased focus on financial reporting and suspicious transaction monitoring\n\n3. Major Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Expanded reporting obligations\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Recent Developments\n- Enhanced customer verification procedures\n- Digital transaction tracking\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Cross-border information sharing\n\n5. Key Legislative Trends\n- Risk-based approach\n- Technology integration\n- Broader regulatory scope\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Continuous adaptation to emerging financial technologies\n\n6. Current Focus\n- Combating terrorist financing\n- Addressing complex financial networks\n- Implementing advanced technological solutions\n- Strengthening global regulatory frameworks\n\nThe evolution reflects increasingly sophisticated approaches to detecting and preventing financial crimes.",
